<p><a href="http://smallbiztrends.com/2013/10/xero-small-business-accounting-software-funding.html">Xero raised $150 million last year</a> largely from U.S. investors to increase its presence in the U.S. market. Now the cloud accounting firm says itâ€™s seen a 200 percent increase in customers hereÂ since 2013.</p>
<p>The actual number of customers is still pretty small â€” just 18,000 in North America. Thatâ€™s compared to much bigger numbers in Australia and its native New Zealand.</p>
<p>The annual report for the companyâ€™s fiscal year ending March 31 was released this week. Company heads said they are committed to growing their business here focused on the small business market.</p>
<p>In the report, Chief Executive Rod Drury and Chairman Chris Liddell:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>â€œDuring this phase we developed a detailed understanding of the U.S. market, and with that knowledge and experience Xero is now building out the balance of the management team and moving appropriate global functions to the U.S. While independent product reviews place Xero strongly against competitors, there are numerous opportunities to create a â€˜best in classâ€™ product for the U.S. market. U.S. specific product development will be a significant focus in the forthcoming year.â€</p>
</blockquote>
<p>New leadership added this year to aid the expansion includes Liddell, who the company calls its independent New York-based chairman of the board. Liddell formerly served both as Vice Chairman and CFO at General Motors and as Senior Vice President and CFO at Microsoft.</p>
<p>Another addition is new CEO of North America, Peter Karpas, who the company says has strong experience in the U.S. small business market.</p>
<p>Xero has also strengthened the U.S. presence on its board of directors with appointment of Bill Veghte. Veghte is the Vice President and Manager of HPâ€™s Enterprise Group.</p>
<p>The company has also increased its U.S. based workforce with an additional 376 employees added mainly in the U.S.</p>
<p>The increase in U.S. staffing has included new software and marketing teams based in San Francisco and a new contact, sales and operation center in Denver.</p>
<p>Xero executives say they have also built a support â€œecosystemâ€ of more than 300 partners. These include accounting firms who use the companyâ€™s software and other third party small business service providers.</p>
<p><strong><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/ShawnHessingerSBT-e1401054012995.jpg"><img class="alignleft wp-image-15596 size-full" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/ShawnHessingerSBT-e1401054012995.jpg" alt="ShawnHessingerSBT" width="100" height="132" /></a>About the Author</strong>: <a title="Shawn Hessigner" href="http://smallbiztrends.com/author/shawn-hessinger" target="_blank">Shawn Hessigner</a> is <span style="color: #333333;">the Editor for <a title="Small Business Trends" href="http://smallbiztrends.com/" target="_blank">Small Business Trends</a>. He is a journalist and social media networker with more than a decade of experience in the traditional newspaper business before moving to the digital world. He was the former community manager of BizSugar and the former community editor at AllAnalytics, a site dedicated to professionals in the business intelligence and analytics community.</span></p>
