<p><em>Photo courtesy of: <a title="Xero" href="http://www.xero.com/nz/" target="_blank">Xero</a>.</em></p>";s:10:"post_title";s:25:"Xero: 200% Increase in US";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:31:"xero-200-percent-increase-in-us";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2014-05-26 09:41:09";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2014-05-25 21:41:09";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:96:"http://aboutus.co.nz/target/xero-sees-200-percent-increase-in-u-s-customers-adds-new-leadership/";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:1;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:5:"15620";s:11:"post_author";s:4:"2616";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-05-26 12:11:57";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-05-26 00:11:57";s:12:"post_content";s:6316:"<p>Let's start from the beginning: I am female. I'm an Aucklander living a short walk away from the CBD. I work, gym and play about 25 hours perÂ day, and say yes to (almost) every opportunity that comes my way. Suffice to say I love to look and feel good all of those hours.Â And suffice to say I really, <em>really</em> don't.Â </p>
<p>Enter my beauty and therapy saviour: <a title="Flossie Concierge" href="https://www.flossie.com/help/what-is-flossie-concierge" target="_blank">Flossie Concierge</a>. If you're familiar with concepts like <a title="lastminute.com" href="http://www.lastminute.co.nz/" target="_blank">lastminute.com</a>Â and <a title="Uber" href="https://www.uber.com/" target="_blank">Uber</a>,Â you'll understand the concept of consumer-led,Â last minuteÂ requests: <em>"I want... who wants me?" </em></p>
<p>When Uber launched in 2009, it sought to solve two business problems: taxis waiting for business; and consumers wanting taxis <em>"Now!"</em>. The Uber team <a title="created an app" href="https://www.uber.com/about" target="_blank">createdÂ an app</a> that connects these two groups without the need for dialogue, and has now connected 70 cities, including our own centralÂ <a title="Auckland" href="https://www.uber.com/cities/auckland" target="_blank">Auckland</a>. Bye bye call centre; hello faster service with the control back in the hands of drivers and travellers.</p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/flossie-concierge-is-coming/"><img class="alignleft" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/flossie-logo-concierge-bp1.png" alt="Flossie Concierge is COMING - Be Ready!" width="281" height="244" /></a></p>
<p>With this in mind, CEO and Founder of <a title="Flossie.com" href="https://www.flossie.com" target="_blank">Flossie.com</a>Â <a title="Jenene Crossman" href="nz.linkedin.com/pub/jenene-crossan/b/643/41a" target="_blank">Jenene Crossan</a> set out to solve the busy woman challenge (and men too, but Flossie has a definite female skew), pairing it with salons Auckland-wide with availableÂ last minute appointments. Crossan and her talented webÂ development teamÂ created Flossie Concierge and are currently putting it through its testing paces before launching onÂ iOS and Android soon.Â </p>
<p>Flossie Concierge is <em>the</em>Â app for consumers to request on-demand hair beauty and therapy appointments on that day, or in the days following (it's not a forward booking system).Â ItÂ alsoÂ solves a massive small business problem in the health and beauty sector,Â which is the inability for most salonsÂ and spas to fill empty on-the-day appointments (without a blackboard outside to entice walk-ins, or clever Facebook, Instagram and Twitter posts - if they are even in fact using social media).</p>
<p>It works by consumers making a health or beautyÂ request - for say, a therapeutic massage, an eyebrow shape, a manicure,Â or hair cut and colourÂ -Â all of which takes about 20 seconds:</p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/flossie-01.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-15625 size-large" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/flossie-01-219x390.png" alt="flossie-01" width="219" height="390" /></a><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/flossie-02.png"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-15626" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/flossie-02-219x390.png" alt="flossie-02" width="219" height="390" /></a></p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/flossie-03.png"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-15627" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/flossie-03-219x390.png" alt="flossie-03" width="219" height="390" /></a><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/flossie-04.png"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-15628" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/flossie-04-219x390.png" alt="flossie-04" width="219" height="390" /></a></p>
<p>A desktop alert is sent to relevant salons and spas and they can send a message immediately offering up to three appointments, whichÂ are sent directly back to the request originator. From there they can browse the options, select the one that appeals most,Â buy it directly within the app, and add it to their smartphoneÂ calendar. The salon receives a desktop message notification and they can then confirm the appointment in their booking system.</p>
<p><a title="Flossie salons and spas" href="https://www.flossie.com/our-salons-and-spas" target="_blank">Flossie salons and spas</a> are selected for their quality of service, style and consistency. The app has been introduced to many of the FlossieÂ participating salon owners all of whom are praising its innovation and are excited to get rolling. Flossie has grown a massive database of users all eager to give Flossie Concierge a go.</p>
<p>I think this app is at the beginning of the wave where consumers lead the drive for small business products and services. I can see this app working for dentists, mechanics, physiotherapists, plumbers and more:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Imagine</strong>: You need four new tyres and there's an app to load inÂ make, model and year of your car, and tyre businesses replies immediatelyÂ with cost and delivery. That's what we're talking about!</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Thanks Jenene and Flossie for leading the charge in the consumer-led app revolution! If you want to be among the first to trial Flossie Concierge, email:Â <a href="mailto:jenene@flossie.com">jenene@flossie.com</a>.</p>
<p><strong><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/belinda-e1399343803578.jpg"><img class="alignleft wp-image-15096 size-full" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/belinda-e1399343803578.jpg" alt="belinda" width="100" height="100" /></a>About the Author</strong>:Â <a title="Belinda Nash" href="nz.linkedin.com/in/belindanash/" target="_blank">Belinda Nash</a>Â is the Content and Community Manager for About Us andÂ Head of Social Media atÂ <a title="Socialize" href="http://www.socialize.co.nz/" target="_blank">Socialize</a>. She has 20+ years experience in media and communications. SheÂ establishedÂ AUT University's social media presence, and has worked with some of New Zealand's most prominent companies.</p>";s:10:"post_title";s:39:"Flossie Concierge is COMING - Be Ready!";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:27:"flossie-concierge-is-coming";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2014-05-26 20:23:03";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2014-05-26 08:23:03";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:54:"http://aboutus.co.nz/target/what-is-flossie-concierge/";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:2;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:5:"15761";s:11:"post_author";s:4:"2616";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-06-13 11:30:38";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-12 23:30:38";s:12:"post_content";s:5554:"<p><em>Picture this</em>: You're on the phone with a customer and you'reÂ trying to make a time to catch up. You say:Â "I'm trying to ascertain your availability so I can diarise some time with you". To which they say: "Erm, what?"</p>
<p>Sounds bloody stupid, doesn't it? No one talks like this. And yet this is how people communicate in email and on websites. Take note that writing in this superfluous, hyper-inflated way doesn't make you look smarter. It makes you look dumb.Â </p>
<p>We're not the only one who think that. Read <a title="Linnet Hunter" href="http://linnethunter.com/" target="_blank">Linnet Hunter</a>'s better plain English tips below. Good advice.</p>
<p id="mct-ai-attriblink"><a href="http://www.startupsmart.com.au/sales-and-marketing/marketing/plain-speaking-and-writing-gets-your-message-across/2014061012468.html?utm_source=StartupSmart&amp;utm_campaign=c80b8c2a52-SmartSolo_6_3_2014&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_term=0_354a773c4a-c80b8c2a52-153477045">Click here to view original web page at www.startupsmart.com.au</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>â€œIf there are any points on which you require explanation or further particulars we shall be glad to furnish such additional details as may be required by telephone.â€</p>
</blockquote>
<p>What the?! This could simply be written as: â€œIf you have any questions, please phone.â€</p>
<p>Okay, so this is a bit of a hokey example, but it is no exaggeration that while the business trend is towards speaking plainly, we still find this kind of bureaucratic doublespeak cropping up.</p>
<p>â€œTell me in plain Englishâ€ is a request we are hearing more and more often. But people who are able to speak with clarity and articulate complex ideas in speech, seem when writing to fall into a kind of language designed to impress rather than inform. Others worry that simplifying their writing is dumbing things down and contributing to a decline in the literacy standards of the free world.</p>
<p>But what happens when we use convoluted sentences, inflated vocabulary and specialist terms? Instead of impressing our reader we probably confuse and annoy them.</p>
<p>If you want your message read, your meaning understood and action taken, then here are four things to keep in front of you while writing emails, letters and reports.</p>
<p><strong>1. Use only as many words as are necessary to carry the message</strong>. Padding it out and buffering your key idea only confuses the reader who has to search for the reason you are writing. If that is hidden in a bushel of other language, they may give up and not read to the end or look any further than the first paragraph.</p>
<p><strong>2. Avoid long words, jargon and acronyms</strong>. Living in our own little world, we often forget that others do not know what a CIO might be or the relevance of the AQTF to their training request. Use the everyday word for things and write as you speak, in short sentences. Using jargon, acronyms and long sentences makes the message more confusing and the likelihood of the letter going into the too hard basket or the bin that much higher.</p>
<p><strong>3. Use short sentences</strong>. Aim for between 15-20 words where possible to help your reader take in the information swiftly.</p>
<p><strong>4. Donâ€™t be afraid to give directions when you are writing instructions</strong>. We often see sentences like 'You are required to return the formâ€™ instead of 'Return the form.'</p>
<p><a title="Tim Costello" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_Costello" target="_blank">Tim Costello</a> recently remarked in a radio interview that the main reason we don't trust politicians is because they don't speak to us in plain English. So this is not just a communication issue, but a way of building trust with the people you work with every day.</p>
<p>By the way, I have just put this article through a readability test and it comes up as written to a Year Nine US reading level. Thatâ€™s not because I think you canâ€™t read beyond that level, but because I know you are busy people who want to take in the message and get the action hints as quickly as possible.</p>
<p><strong><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/linnet-hunter-e1402629474970.jpg"><img class="alignleft wp-image-15809 size-full" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/linnet-hunter-e1402629474970.jpg" alt="linnet-hunter" width="100" height="118" /></a>About the Author</strong>: Linnet HunterÂ <span style="color: #666666;">is an intuitive coach, inspired facilitator and memorable speaker who works in creative conversations for change. She loves listening, is incurably curious about people and is named after a bird, which she reckons is a licence to tweet! Go toÂ </span><a style="color: #666666;" title="http://linnethunter.com/" href="http://linnethunter.com/" target="_blank">linnethunter.com</a>Â <span style="color: #666666;">to read her blog or visit <a title="Wild Sky" href="http://www.wildsky.com.au/" target="_blank">Wild Sky</a>.</span></p>
<p><a href="http://www.startupsmart.com.au/sales-and-marketing/marketing/plain-speaking-and-writing-gets-your-message-across/2014061012468.html?utm_source=StartupSmart&amp;utm_campaign=c80b8c2a52-SmartSolo_6_3_2014&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_term=0_354a773c4a-c80b8c2a52-153477045">Click here to view original web page at www.startupsmart.com.au</a></p>
<p><em>Photo courtesy of: <a title="Rotten Cards" href="http://m.rottenecards.com/cards/denise_wilson/?page=19" target="_blank">Rotten Cards</a>.</em></p>";s:10:"post_title";s:29:"Lose The BS and Speak Plainly";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:29:"lose-the-bs-and-speak-plainly";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2014-06-13 15:36:36";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-13 03:36:36";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:80:"http://aboutus.co.nz/target/plain-speaking-and-writing-gets-your-message-across/";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:3;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:5:"15799";s:11:"post_author";s:4:"2616";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-06-13 15:09:41";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-13 03:09:41";s:12:"post_content";s:5087:"<p>I have been on the road for the past month with <a href="https://www.flossie.com/">Flossie.com</a> showcasing its new app <a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/flossie-concierge-is-coming/">Flossie Concierge</a> to Aucklandâ€™s high-end health and beauty spas and salons. I have beaten a path down some of New Zealandâ€™s most exclusive streets â€“ from Herne Bay, Ponsonby, Parnell, Devonport, Takapuna, Newmarket, Epsom and Remuera. And you may be as surprised as I am to learn that some of these businesses are barely using the Internet at all â€“ let alone accessing cloud services or transferring their social skills to social media.</p>
<p><a href="http://thebigupgradeblog.tumblr.com/post/81415666821/thirty-four-billion-freaking-dollars">The $34 billion dollar loss story</a> is real, and itâ€™s happening right now on our most affluent doorsteps. And this is a profound failure.</p>
<p>Make no mistake; these salon owners are savvy, smart business operators at the <em>very</em> top of their game. <em>But</em> the Internet â€“ or those who hold the knowledge on how the Internet can enable better business productivity and efficiency â€“ has passed them by. They have been left completely in the dark, and every day this should cause alarm to the telcos, cloud service companies, people building new technology, and the people running our country.</p>
<p>We behind desks have our heads in the cloud. Literally.</p>
<p>What's more, there have been so many snake oil salespeople and â€œgurusâ€ taint the market that the mere mention of the word â€œappâ€ is greeted with suspicion. I am just another trickster out to hustle their well-earned dollar. (I met a small business owner the other day who had a charlatan offer to set them up with GeoOp for $500 when install is free, quick and simple and begins with a no-cost trial. Thatâ€™s a pretty good business model: installing a free cloud service for $500 a time).</p>
<p>Something has to be done and it must be done very bloody fast, or we all might as well pack up and go home.Â Â </p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/book-keeping.jpg"><img class="alignleft wp-image-15806 size-medium" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/book-keeping-266x266.jpg" alt="book-keeping" width="266" height="266" /></a>Back to the Auckland businesses I am visiting. It is not unusual for these salons and spas to run entirely on paper â€“ from stock inventory, appointment bookings through to accounts. Itâ€™s also not unusual for the business to have no computer or wifi access â€“ or even a business email address (I counted three on Aucklandâ€™s High Street). And for the businesses that do have wifi, about five per cent know their wifi password.</p>
<p>Some of these businesses â€“ full of hugely talented, marvellously skilled people â€“ run their operations in the year 1995. Getting these spas and salons â€“ that form the heart of Kiwi small businesses and employ the largest part of our population â€“ into using social media and cloud apps is, frankly, daydreaming to the nth degree. As it stands, this is not going to happen.</p>
<p>So what are we going to do about it?</p>
<p>This is a New Zealand problem and it needs a dedicated, swift, comprehensive New Zealand solution. Big business needs to link arms and form a sustainable, affordable solution that enables, educates and equips small businesses to use the Internet for better business. And itâ€™s happening. <a href="http://aboutus.co.nz">About Us</a> has support of big business and is on a mission to bring the best of the worldâ€™s knowledge on topics from e-commerce, blogging, SEO, cloud services, mobile hardware onto the screens of small business owners. Weâ€™re giving every business owner a free business web profile page, and educating them by showcasing exemplars and the best apps to make their business bottom line better.</p>
<p><em>But</em> we have to ensure we gain the trust of a community that has been sold many lemons, and that all Kiwi businesses have access to the technology to join the digital business age. And it's up to all of us.</p>
<p><strong><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/belinda1-e1401076711759.jpg"><img class="alignleft wp-image-15666 size-full" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/belinda1-e1401076711759.jpg" alt="belinda" width="100" height="100" /></a>About the Author</strong>:Â <a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-admin/nz.linkedin.com/in/belindanash">Belinda Nash</a>Â is the Content and Community Manager for About Us, Head of Social Media atÂ <a href="http://www.socialize.co.nz/">Socialize</a>, and Advisor to theÂ <a href="http://www.keanewzealand.com/">Kea New Zealand</a>Â Global Board. She has 20+ years experience in media and communications. SheÂ establishedÂ AUT University's social media presence, and has worked with some of New Zealand's most prominent companies.</p>
<p><em>Photo courtesy of: <a title="Bold Perspective" href="http://boldperspective.com/2011/fail-thats-a-command/" target="_blank">Bold Perspective</a>.</em></p>";s:10:"post_title";s:38:"The Internet Has Failed Small Business";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:38:"the-internet-has-failed-small-business";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2014-06-13 15:09:41";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-13 03:09:41";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:29:"http://aboutus.co.nz/?p=15799";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:4;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:5:"15815";s:11:"post_author";s:4:"2616";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-06-16 10:10:40";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-15 22:10:40";s:12:"post_content";s:2283:"<p>This year's <a title="Gen-i FWD_Live 2014 conference" href="http://www.gen-i.co.nz/insights/fwd-programme/fwd-live/" target="_blank">Gen-i FWD_Live 2014 conference</a>, held on May 1, focussed on cultural shift for businesses where the customer is at the centre of any product or service. CEO Tim Miles stressed that it's not aboutÂ the tools of connectivity, rather the people who use it, saying:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>"We have the opportunity for the first time, instead of focussing our business around a piece of copper wire or a piece of fibre, we now can truly centre our business around you, our customer."</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I was fortunate to be invited to join a panel discussion atÂ FWD_Live facilitated by Gen-i chief marketing officer Jo Allison, who asked:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>"What do you think the biggest challenge is that businesses are facing in the age of the connected customer?"</p>
</blockquote>
<p>You can hear our replies here:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<iframe width="640" height="390" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/sINRJfisu5g" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Or watch the summary video below:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Â <iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/mXinbfQtl_s" width="640" height="390" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
<p><strong><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/belinda-e1402623970815.jpg"><img class="alignleft wp-image-15786 size-full" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/belinda-e1402623970815.jpg" alt="belinda" width="100" height="100" /></a>About the Author</strong>:Â <a href="nz.linkedin.com:in:belindanash">Belinda Nash</a> is the Content and Community Manager for About Us, Head of Social Media at <a href="http://www.socialize.co.nz/">Socialize</a>, and Advisor to the <a href="http://www.keanewzealand.com/">Kea New Zealand</a> Global Board. She has 20+ years experience in media and communications. SheÂ establishedÂ AUT University's social media presence, and has worked with some of New Zealand's most prominent companies.</p>
<p>Photo courtesy of: <a title="Evan Carmichael" href="http://www.evancarmichael.com/blog/2009/09/15/customer-service-idea-1-read-the-out-of-office-replies/" target="_blank">Evan Carmichael</a>.</p>";s:10:"post_title";s:35:"Putting Your Customer at the Centre";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:35:"putting-your-customer-at-the-centre";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2014-06-16 10:20:18";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-15 22:20:18";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:29:"http://aboutus.co.nz/?p=15815";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:5;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:5:"15829";s:11:"post_author";s:4:"2616";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-06-16 12:20:54";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-16 00:20:54";s:12:"post_content";s:4736:"<p>This September I'll be joining public relations stalwarts at theÂ <span style="color: #222222;">Inside Story Communications &amp; Media Relations Conference onÂ </span>at the Crowne Plaza Hotel in Auckland. We'll be debating the topic:Â <em><span lang="EN-GB">Have new media channels rendered traditional PR dead?</span></em></p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/inside-story.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-15830" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/inside-story.png" alt="inside-story" width="942" height="194" /></a></p>
<p>While I'll be arguing the affirmative, I think the truth lies moreÂ inÂ that PR companies need to take hold of and <em>master</em> new mediaÂ tools - such as blogs and social media - and use them less to "market" and get "key messages" out, and more to lead, listen and connect. And this takes boldness from the people who employ PR professionals.</p>
<p>Authentic PR delivery isÂ the result of research - and part of that research involves listening to your customers and potential customers. What do they want, and do they want what you're offering?</p>
<p>My attention was drawn to this week's,Â <em>The Washington Post</em>'s <a title="Job of the Week" href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/business/capitalbusiness/job-of-the-week-riding-the-rails-to-craft-amtraks-social-media-strategy/2014/06/13/86069b54-f184-11e3-9ebc-2ee6f81ed217_story.html" target="_blank">Job of the Week</a>.Â <span style="color: #333333;">Amtrakâ€™s director of social media <a title="Julie Quinn" href="https://twitter.com/JuliaAQuinn" target="_blank">Julie Quinn</a> talks with web editor <a title="Sarah Halzack" href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/pb/sarah-halzack" target="_blank">Sarah Halzack</a>Â and shares Amtrak's social media strategy:</span></p>
<p><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-16-at-11.32.23-AM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-15832" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-shot-2014-06-16-at-11.32.23-AM.png" alt="Screen shot 2014-06-16 at 11.32.23 AM" width="641" height="300" /></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>What I think stands out inÂ this statement is that <a title="Amtrak" href="https://twitter.com/Amtrak" target="_blank">Amtrak</a>Â prioritises listening to customer feedback, whether it's good, bad or ugly. Naturally, the chain of command back into the business needs to receive the feedback in good faith and act upon it. (Otherwise the exercise is pointless).</p>
<p>I've worked with businessesÂ where social media is taken seriously. And with others where it's seen as a nice-to-have for brand positioning but the social media operative isÂ not supported in feeding back their intel into the business where it can beÂ heard at the highest level. ThisÂ means the organisation isÂ not even getting the mostÂ from theirÂ social media person, or team, and channels. I predict that oneÂ day this organisational blindness may prove fatal to the business' future.</p>
<p>Make no mistake, whether your customers are using social media channels like Twitter, they're part of Twitter's reach every day. OurÂ news media channels deliver a constant dietÂ of information gleanedÂ from Twitter - just search the word on <em><a title="The New Zealand Herald's website" href="http://www.nzherald.co.nz/twitter/search/results.cfm?kw1=twitter&amp;kw2=&amp;st=gsa" target="_blank">The New Zealand Herald</a>'sÂ </em>website, as an example, as see how many results some up. So if you stuff up, it will reach the ears of your consumers, past, present and future.</p>
<p>So yes, if PR doesn't get the social media basics right and advise the businesses they work for accordingly, they and PR are dead in the water.</p>
<p><strong><a href="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/belinda-e1402623970815.jpg"><img class="alignleft wp-image-15786 size-full" src="http://aboutus.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/belinda-e1402623970815.jpg" alt="belinda" width="100" height="100" /></a>About the Author</strong>:Â <a href="nz.linkedin.com:in:belindanash">Belinda Nash</a> is the Content and Community Manager for About Us, Head of Social Media at <a href="http://www.socialize.co.nz/">Socialize</a>, and Advisor to the <a href="http://www.keanewzealand.com/">Kea New Zealand</a> Global Board. She has 20+ years experience in media and communications. SheÂ establishedÂ AUT University's social media presence, and has worked with some of New Zealand's most prominent companies.</p>
<p><em>Photo courtesy of: <a title="Zazzle.co.nz" href="http://www.zazzle.co.nz/dont_interrupt_me_while_im_ignoring_you_tshirt-235959599931044143" target="_blank">Zazzle.co.nz</a>.</em></p>";s:10:"post_title";s:21:"You're Not Listening!";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:19:"youre-not-listening";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2014-06-16 12:20:54";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-16 00:20:54";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:29:"http://aboutus.co.nz/?p=15829";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:6;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:5:"15844";s:11:"post_author";s:4:"2616";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-06-16 14:32:45";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-06-16 02:32:45";s:12:"post_content";s:5034:"<p>Last week we wrote about how <a title="the Internet has failed small business" href="http://aboutus.co.nz/the-internet-has-failed-small-business/" target="_blank">the Internet has failed small business</a>. It strikes us, thisÂ isÂ as much about big business' failure to help increase the knowledge of small businesses in using the Internet, and small business forÂ hiding behind fear and doing "what we've always done".</p>
<p>Regardless, the Internet and social media is not working for small business. Marketing "diva" at Marketed by Michelle,Â <a title="Michelle Ames" href="www.linkedin.com/in/michellefrechetteames" target="_blank">Michelle Ames</a>Â digs under what she thinks is the cause and throws out a few solutions.</p>
<p id="mct-ai-attriblink"><a href="http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/money/business/2014/06/11/ames-small-businesses-underuse-social-media/10291303/">Click here to view original web page at www.democratandchronicle.com</a></p>
<p>I am often asked by business owners which social media sites they should use for their small businesses, and whether they should be using social media at all.</p>
<p>My answer is always the same: it depends.</p>
<p>Many businesses believe they can make a decision whether or not to have an online business presence. Those days have been gone for a long time. A search of your business name online will likely reveal that it already exists in many places, and that clients and customers are already engaging with you online even if you are not aware of it.</p>
<p>Determining which sites to use can be overwhelming. Marketing your business through social media should be no different than marketing in any other way â€” it should be targeted to your audience.</p>
<p>Major social sites include: Facebook, Twitter, LinkedIn, Pinterest, Instagram, YouTube, Google+, Vine and Foursquare; and feedback venues like Yelp, Google+ Business, Angieâ€™s List, Yahoo! Local, Yellow Pages and Urbanspoon.</p>
<p>So how do you know which ones are best for your business?</p>
<p>Start by looking at the average age of your target audience and compare it to the average age of the siteâ€™s users. Targeting teens and twenty-somethings? Instagram may be your best bet. Busy professionals on the go? Twitterâ€™s 140-character limit broadcasts bite-sized pieces that are quick and easy to digest. Adult women? Pinterest is influential for that audience.</p>
<p>Is your product or service something that is showcased better in video? Creating a YouTube channel from which to post videos to your website and other social media sites can be advantageous.</p>
<p>Is your product or service something that most people can make a decision regarding? Like clothing or food? Or is your business selling clean rooms to hospitals? The answer to those questions will determine which sites are best for you.</p>
<p>LinkedIn, for example, is better used for business-to-business growth and personal rÃ©sumÃ© connections than Facebook or Pinterest.</p>
<p>Facebook continues to hold the largest number of subscribers with the greatest variety in utility. Users engage with each other and with business pages, games, videos, photos and more. Facebookâ€™s users range in age from teens through adults of all ages. Check-ins on Facebook mimic Foursquareâ€™s check-ins and businesses can be rated on Facebook like they can on Foursquare, Yelp and other sites.</p>
<p>Perhaps the biggest oversight by many businesses is the failure to claim listings on sites where clients are already engaging, sites like Angieâ€™s List, Yelp, and Google+ Business. By claiming your listing there, you have the ability to shape the customerâ€™s experience. You can upload logos and photos, and complete your listing to include contact information, hours, location and business history. You can also dialogue with members who have commented on your business â€” good and bad.</p>
<p>One of the worst things a business can do is create a social media page and not use it. The key to client engagement is business commitment. So post well, and post often.</p>
